ic <b>Mac Fearadhaigh</b>, itself an unlenited and subsequently voiced variant of <b>Mac Fhearadhaigh</b>, ‘son of <i>Fearadhach</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘manly’. Compare   McAree   and   McCary  ; also the surnames   Ferry   and   Farry  , from <i>Ó Fearadhaigh</i>.","History: The widow Bridget Very settled with her children in Salem, MA, <i>c.</i> 1634. She had many prominent descendants, including the poet Jones Very (1813–1880)."],"variants":[{"name":"McAree","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhearadhaigh</b> ‘son of <i>Fearadhach</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘manly’ (from <i>fear</i> ‘man’). Pronunciation of this name as <i>McAree</i> led to misinterpretation as <i>Mac an Rí</i> ‘son of the king’ and thus to ‘translation’ as   King  . See   McGarry  ."]}]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Simon de Vergy was born in 1081, in Reulle-Vergy, Côte-d'Or, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, France as the son of Simon DE VERGY. He had at least 2 sons with Amicie DE VENDEUIL. He died in 1140, in Châtel-Censoir, Yonne, Burgundy, France, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1081–1140":"1081–1140","1092–1143":"1092–1143","1087–1114":"1087–1114","1101–1175":"1101–1175","1115–1191":"1115–1191","10